President Donald J. Trump has announced his intent to nominate Richard Clarida of Connecticut as Vice Chairman of the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System. Clarida is currently a professor of economics at Columbia University and has previously taught at Yale University. He has also served as Assistant Secretary for Economic Policy at the U.S. Treasury and has been a Global Strategic Advisor for PIMCO since 2006. Clarida earned his B.S. in economics from the University of Illinois and his M.A. and Ph.D. in economics from Harvard University.

Additionally, Dan Michael Berkovitz of Maryland has been nominated to be Commissioner of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission. Berkovitz is currently a partner and co-chair of the futures and derivatives practice at the law firm of WilmerHale. He has previously served as General Counsel of the U.S. Commodity Futures Trading Commission and as Deputy Assistant Secretary in the Department of Energyâ€™s Office of Environmental Management. Berkovitz obtained an A.B. in Physics from Princeton University and a J.D. from the University of California, Hastings College of the Law.

Furthermore, Michelle Bowman of Kansas has been nominated to be a Member of the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System as the Community Bank Representative representing Region 8. Bowman currently serves as the Kansas State Bank Commissioner and is the first woman appointed and confirmed to this position by the Kansas State Senate. She has also held various positions in government, including working for Senator Bob Dole and serving as Director of Congressional and Intergovernmental Affairs at the Federal Emergency Management Agency. Bowman graduated from the University of Kansas and received a J.D. from Washburn University School of Law.